data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has **three** patterns that need migration:

| Location | Pattern | API |
|----------|---------|-----|
| `Stop()` | Blocking call interruption | `Thread.Interrupt()` |
| `Stop()` | Timeout enforcement / forced kill | `Thread.Abort()` |
| `RunLoop()` | Cancellable work loop | `while (true)` with no exit |

### Migrated Code (Direct)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new object();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Wait for new-event OR cancellation — replaces Thread.Interrupt wake-up
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(
                new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle });

            if (signaled == 1) // token.WaitHandle fired → stop requested
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            string? item = null;
            lock (_lock)
            {
                if (_queue.Count > 0)
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
            }

            if (item is not null)
                Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        // Cooperative cancellation replaces both Interrupt and Abort
        _cts.Cancel();           // wakes WaitAny via token.WaitHandle
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // still give thread time to exit cleanly
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Original | Replacement | Reason |
|----------|-------------|--------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | `Interrupt` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9). `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` wakes the blocked thread cooperatively. |
| `Thread.Abort()` | removed | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006`). Cooperative cancellation means the loop exits on its own — no forced kill needed. |
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Loop must voluntarily check for cancellation. |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle })` | Lets either a new event **or** cancellation wake the thread. |
| — | `IDisposable` added | `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` are disposable; leaking them causes timer/callback leaks. |

### Pitfalls specific to this code

1. **Race in the original design** — If multiple `Enqueue` calls fire between `WaitOne` returning and `Reset`, signals are lost and items sit in the queue. The migrated code adds a defensive `_queue.Count > 0` check to avoid an `InvalidOperationException`, but the signal-loss race remains. Consider `BlockingCollection<T>` (below) if this matters.

2. **`Handle()` must not block indefinitely** — Cooperative cancellation only takes effect at the `WaitAny` checkpoint. If `Handle(item)` hangs, `Stop()` will still block at `Join(5000)`. If `Handle` does I/O, pass the `CancellationToken` through it.

3. **Don't forget `Dispose`** — The original code never disposed the `ManualResetEvent`. The new code adds `IDisposable` to clean up both it and the `CancellationTokenSource`.

### Idiomatic alternative (recommended)

`BlockingCollection<T>` eliminates the manual event + lock + queue entirely and fixes the signal-loss race:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        // GetConsumingEnumerable blocks until an item arrives
        // and exits cleanly when CompleteAdding is called.
        foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable())
            Handle(item);
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _queue.Add(item);

    public void Stop()
    {
        _queue.CompleteAdding(); // RunLoop's foreach exits
        _thread?.Join(5000);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _queue.Dispose();
    }
}
```

This is the preferred .NET 8 approach — no `Thread.Abort`, no `Thread.Interrupt`, no manual synchronization, and no lost signals.
